snippet.textDisplay: Yes, the rest of the game was(for the most part) light and cheerful. But I just said that the ENDING was dark. And the rest of the game wasn't entirely happy-go-lucky either. The ending was built up throughout a large portion of the game, as each boss you killed (starting with Slime Eel) warned against waking the Wind Fish. That, along with the ominous message at the southern Face Shrine and what some owl statues said, created a sense of dread that contrasted with the game's lighter tones.
snippet.textOriginal: Yes, the rest of the game was(for the most part) light and cheerful. But I just said that the ENDING was dark. And the rest of the game wasn't entirely happy-go-lucky either. The ending was built up throughout a large portion of the game, as each boss you killed (starting with Slime Eel) warned against waking the Wind Fish. That, along with the ominous message at the southern Face Shrine and what some owl statues said, created a sense of dread that contrasted with the game's lighter tones.

snippet.textDisplay: Not dark? Link's actions end up destroying the entire world you've been exploring throughout the entire game. You watch as everything and everyone you've grown to know and love over the course of your journey is annihilated and Koholint Island is wiped from existence. Link brings Koholint to an end so that he may return to Hyrule. The whole ending has a sort of "lesser evil for the greater good" theme to it, sacrificing Koholint for Hyrule. Is that not a dark ending?

snippet.textDisplay:
When I was a kid, I always swore to never be a 'nostalgic old fogey', who longs for the "good old days" about anything, and embrace everything right about the new. But... the old days of gaming... they really did seem so much better. I miss them.

When I was a kid, I didn't think gaming would change like it has. There are still plenty of good new games, true. But things just aren't the same. They aren't quite as good. It's just.... it's just not the same. It's not the 16-Bit era.
